'''Maiko Roku Shrine''' (舞子六神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Tarumi Ward|ja|垂水区|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kobe City|ja|神戸市|12=draft}}, {{ill|Hyogo Prefecture|ja|兵庫県|12=draft}}. The shrine features large stone statues of {{ill|Ebisu (god)|ja|戎|12=draft}} and {{ill|Daikokuten|ja|大黒天|12=draft}}, which are said to be the largest in Japan.

== History ==
The shrine's foundation can be traced back to {{ill|1689|ja|元禄|12=draft}} (Genroku 2), as evidenced by inscriptions on the golden staff carried during the mikoshi procession. However, due to the loss of historical records, details prior to this period remain unclear. The shrine's deities are the same as those of the {{ill|Iwaya Shrine (Akashi)|ja|岩屋神社 (明石市)|12=draft}} in Akashi, suggesting that its foundation dates to the early Edo period, when spirits from Iwaya Shrine were enshrined here. The shrine served as the general {{ill|Chinju|ja|鎮守|12=draft}} (village guardian) of Yamada Village in Harima Province.

Following the {{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|ja|神仏分離|12=draft}} (separation of Shinto and Buddhism) decree in the early Meiji era, the shrine's name changed from "Rokusha Daimyōjin" to "Rokusha Shrine" in 1874 (Meiji 7). It was later renamed "Roku Shrine," and the current main hall, rebuilt in 1890 (Meiji 23), was renovated with a copper roof between 1906 and 1907.

== Enshrined Deities ==
* {{ill|Izanagi|ja|伊邪那岐大神|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Izanami|ja|伊邪那美大神|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照皇大神|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Susanoo|ja|素盞男大神|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Tsukuyomi|ja|月夜見大神|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Hiruko|ja|蛭子大神|12=draft}}

== Sub-Shrines ==
* Ōtoshisha (豊宇気比賣命)
* Shirahige-sha (Kifune Taisha)
* Ebisu-miya (Hiruko Taisha)
* Inari Omatsu-sha (Kurainatama Taisha)
* Inari Gosha (Inari Ōkami)
* Sugawara-sha (Sugawara Taisha)
* Daikoku-miya ({{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大国主命|12=draft}})

== Festivals ==
The annual autumn festival is held on the second Sunday of October, with a preparatory night festival on the preceding Saturday. Festivities include mikoshi (portable shrines) and {{ill|Futondaiko|ja|布団太鼓|12=draft}} processions. A traditional boat procession was previously part of the celebrations but is no longer conducted. Other festivals, such as Setsubun and summer festivals, are also held.

=== Futon Daiko ===
The original futon daiko was lost in a storage fire, leaving only mikoshi for the autumn festival for many years. The current futon daiko was acquired from {{ill|Iwaya Shrine (Akashi)|ja|岩屋神社 (明石市)|12=draft}}, which donated it after commissioning a new one. The "Futon Daiko Maiko Association" oversees its management and parade.

== Access ==
* Nearest station: {{ill|Nishi-Maiko Station|ja|西舞子駅|12=draft}} on the {{ill|Sanyo Electric Railway|ja|山陽電気鉄道|12=draft}}, 3 minutes on foot; or {{ill|Maiko Station|ja|舞子駅|12=draft}} on the JR line, 7 minutes on foot.
* Parking available.

== Related Articles ==
* {{ill|Futondaiko|ja|布団太鼓|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Mikoshi|ja|神輿|12=draft}}

== External Links ==
* [https://rokujinjya.jp/ Official Website]

