== History ==
The shrine's foundation can be traced back to {{ill|Genroku|en|Genroku|qid=Q1325001|lt=1689|1=Genroku}} (Genroku 2), as evidenced by inscriptions on the golden staff carried during the mikoshi procession. However, due to the loss of historical records, details prior to this period remain unclear. The shrine's deities are the same as those of the {{ill|Iwaya Shrine (Akashi)|ja|岩屋神社 (明石市)|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iwaya Shrine (Akashi)|1=Iwaya Shrine|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11474394}} in Akashi, suggesting that its foundation dates to the early Edo period, when spirits from Iwaya Shrine were enshrined here. The shrine served as the general {{ill|Chinju|ja|鎮守|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chinju|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 鎮守神|1=Chinjugami|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q97479976}} (village guardian) of Yamada Village in Harima Province.

Following the {{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|en|Shinbutsu bunri|qid=Q1970535|lt=Shinbutsu bunri|1=Shinbutsu bunri}} (separation of Shinto and Buddhism) decree in the early Meiji era, the shrine's name changed from "Rokusha Daimyōjin" to "Rokusha Shrine" in 1874 (Meiji 7). It was later renamed "Roku Shrine," and the current main hall, rebuilt in 1890 (Meiji 23), was renovated with a copper roof between 1906 and 1907.

